[With regard to bats, the following (edited) comment has been received from ProMED-mail subscriber Merritt Clifton:

"For what it's worth, I continue to suspect that the real culprit behind MERS-CoV will turn out to be neither a camel nor a fruit bat, but rather an insectivorous bat -- probably a very tiny insectivorous bat whose diet includes both fruit flies from dates and some of the very small flies who nest in camels' dense hair.

"Camels, because of their size and the density of their hair, which is mostly short but thick enough to protect them against blowing sand, host far more insects than most other animals -- most of them relatively harmless mites, small flies, etc. If you brush a camel's coat, you'll be astonished at the size and diversity of the insect zoo that collects among the loose fur: crawling, flying, larvae, eggs, et al."

Clifton's speculation on the possible involvement of arthropods in MERS-CoV epidemiology is in need of information on the infection dynamics in camels; do they undergo a viraemic phase? If yes, what is its duration and virus load? These, and other aspects of possible animal roles in the disease transmission, could become available if experimental infection trials are realised. The need for such trials, raised in the past, has been pointed at recently in OIE's updated MERS-CoV Q&A page of 12 May 2014 (see commentaries in 20140517.2478989 and 20140523.2493556). - Mod.AS]

