[4] Oman, regional FAO-organised consultation meeting
Date: Wed 21 May 2014
Source: Oman Observer [edited]
http://main.omanobserver.om/?p=82887


The 2-day Regional Technical Consultation Meeting on MERS-CoV and Animals that brought 50 of the region's and the worlds experts to work together, share information and expertise and decide on the best way forward in battling this deadly virus, which records show has already infected over 600 people and caused 188 deaths, concluded here yesterday [20 May 2014]. In order to halt its spread, delegates called for a united stand and positive commitment to eliminate MERS-CoV.

Yesterday's sessions reviewed the current situation of MERS-CoV in Yemen, Qatar, Jordan and a case study from Bahrain. There were also a number of presentations and discussions, as well as outlined conclusions and recommendations. The final session saw local, regional and FAO (Food and Agriculture Organisation of the United Nations) give their deliberations. This meeting was organised by the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in cooperation with FAO. The Observer spoke to participants including Dr Juan Lubroth, chief veterinary officer, FAO, and Ernie Colaizzi, laboratory director of Research Associates Laboratory (RAL) about the meeting and MERS-CoV. Dr Lubroth noted: "This is the 1st regional conference that we've had on this subject and we're very grateful for the Sultanate of Oman for hosting it.

"The Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries have been very transparent with their findings of MERS in the animal population. And I think it's been admirable, in the way the Ministry of Health and the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries have handled it." He explained, "MERS is caused by coronavirus, but there are many different types of coronaviruses, that we know of, some causing mild disease in children and some causing severe disease ­- like the severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) that started in China and spread to Singapore and Canada, killing 800 people before it was stopped."

Commenting on a study conducted on camels in the region and in Spain, he said, "It is interesting because the Canary Islands are off the coast of Africa ­- it's a province that belongs to the Iberian peninsula ­- and it was a closed population, meaning that 18 years ago camels were brought in for tourism, but they stopped bringing in animals 18 years ago. So it was a closed population, no new introduction, yet 15 per cent of them were positive, so we suspect it is an old infection of camels ­- not a disease ­- because we do not see laudable clinical signs in camels." Regarding where the disease emanates from, he pointed out, "We have to keep an open mind, we should look at other animals ­- we know that many different types of coronavirus are in different animals ­- are camels the source or are they also innocent bystanders? We do not know."

In his comments Colaizzi, noted the need is to identify the source and type, saying, "Camels have been testing positive for 2 of them, but what percentage do test positive? We don't know." So do we exclude camels from your society? No, they are too economically important. What about camel meat consumption? Will people get MERS by eating camel meat and drinking camel's milk? That's kind of been the thought, but none of that's been proven. So, the race is on to try and find out what is really going on with this organism in both man and camels and any other sources that there may be. Is the virus coming from bats to camels? Is it from insects to camels? Or is just camels to camels?

"There are so many unanswered questions that it's a race for time. We don't want this to blow up into a pandemic and with Ramadhan coming up (with people going on Umrah and later on Haj) do we now have millions of people catch MERS and spread it out? There are 9 countries that have had MERS outbreaks. We're not sure how they got infected; we're sure some health workers contracted the disease from infected people in hospitals. It does look like it's spreading real quickly from person to person at this point in time. But again, the knowledge is so minimal; what we say now may turn out to be nothing and this is the end of it, or it may turn out into something that quickly explodes, a pandemic."

[byline: Ali Ahmed al Riyami]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Though the information on the possible role of camels in MERS-CoV maintenance and transmission has increased significantly since the fall of 2013, many questions remain to be clarified. Diagnosis of MERS-CoV infection in camels has, so far, been reported to the OIE (as an emergency/zoonotic disease) from 2 countries: Qatar and Oman. Similar reports are anticipated from other affected countries, particularly Saudi Arabia.

Serological investigations are suggestive of the long-standing circulation of MERS-CoV (or its close relatives?) in Ethiopia, Nigeria, Tunisia, Kenya and probably Egypt. Similar situation may prevail in other parts of Africa (and elsewhere). To evaluate the significance of these findings and draw conclusions, serosurveys in persons handling dromedary camels in these countries are in urgent need.

The approaching mass gatherings of pilgrims in Saudi Arabia will require decisions which, besides the need of being scientifically sound, may be influenced by political, economical and other considerations. For one: should contact between the pilgrims and local camels be controlled/limited? One wonders if the epidemiological information, accumulated so far, allows professionals to provide sound, unequivocal advice to politicians at this stage. - Mod.AS]
